{"parse":{"title":"door","pageid":8111,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|döör|Döör|door-}}\n==English==\n{{wp|<dab!>}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|doore|durre||obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰwer-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|dore}}, {{m|enm|dor}}, from {{inh|en|ang|duru||door}}, {{m|ang|dor||gate}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*dur}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*durz}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*dʰwṓr}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*dʰwer-||doorway, door, gate}}.\n\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|door||door}}, {{cog|stq|Doore||door}}, {{cog|fy|doar||door}}, {{cog|nl|deur||door}}, {{cog|nds-de|Door}}, {{m|nds-de|Döör||door}}, {{cog|de|Tür||door}}, {{m|de|Tor||gate}}, {{cog|da,nrn,nb,nn|dør||door}}, {{cog|sv|dörr||door}}, {{cog|fo,is|dyr||door}}, {{cog|ast|-}}, {{cog|an,es|fuera||outside}}, {{cog|ca,roa-leo,pt|fora||outside}}, {{cog|fr|hors||outside}}, {{cog|gl|fóra||outside}}, {{cog|it|fuori||outside}}, {{cog|mwl|fuora||outside}}, {{cog|la|foris}} and {{m|la|foras||outside}}, {{cog|grc|θύρα}}, {{cog|sq|derë||door}}, {{cog|ckb|دەرگە||door}}, {{cog|kmr|derî||door}}, {{cog|fa|در|tr=dar||door}}, {{cog|be|дзве́ры|tr=dzvjéry||door}}, {{cog|bg|две́ри|tr=dvéri||royal doors}}, {{cog|cs|dveře||door}}, {{cog|lv|durvis||door}}, {{cog|lt|durys||door}}, {{cog|mk|двер||door}}, {{cog|pl|drzwi||door}}, {{cog|ru|дверь}}, {{cog|sh|dvȇri||door}}, {{m|sh|dvar||door}}, {{cog|uk|две́рі|tr=dvéri||door}}, {{cog|hi|द्वार||door}}, {{cog|hy|դուռ||door}}, {{cog|ga|doras||door}}, {{cog|sa|द्वार||door}}.\n\nDespite similarities in spelling, not cognate with {{ncog|nl|door}}, which is instead cognate with English {{m|en|en|through}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n[[Image:1 bis place de l'Alma (Paris).jpg|thumb|right|A door]]\n[[Image:9, Strada Spătarului, Bucharest (Romania) 1.jpg|A wooden '''door'''|thumb|right]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{enPR|dōr|aa=non-horse-hoarse}}\n* {{IPA|en|/do(ː)ɹ/|aa=rhotic}}\n* {{IPA|en|/doə/|aa=non-rhotic}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ɖoɾ/|aa=Indic,rhotic}}\n\n{{enPR|dō|aa=non-rhotic,<<non-horse-hoarse>> but with the <<dough-door>>}}\n* {{hmp |en|dough}}\n* {{IPA|en|/doʊ/|aa=AAVE}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ɖo/|aa=Indic}}\n\n{{enPR|dôr|aa=rhotic,horse-hoarse}}\n* {{homophones|en|d'or}}\n* {{IPA|en|/doɹ/|aa=GenAm,Canada}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-door.ogg|a=US}}\n\n{{enPR|dô|aa=non-rhotic,horse-hoarse}}\n* {{hmp|en|d'or|daw}}\n* {{IPA|en|/dɔː/|aa=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-door.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{IPA|en|/doː/|aa=SSB,AU,NZ}}\n\n{{enPR|do͝or}}\n* {{IPA|en|/dʊə/|aa=Yorkshire}}\n* {{homophones|en|dour|aa=one pronunciation}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|architecture}} A {{l|en|portal}} of entry into a building, room, or vehicle, typically consisting of a rigid plane movable on a {{l|en|hinge}}. It may have a {{l|en|handle}} to help open and close, a {{l|en|latch}} to hold it closed{{,}} and a {{l|en|lock}} that ensures it cannot be opened without a key.\n#: {{ux|en|I knocked on the vice president's '''door'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|That's the '''door''' to the bathroom.}}\n#: {{hyper|en|doorway}}\n#: {{hypo|en|back door|barn door|car door|front door|plantation door|revolving door|screen door|side door|sliding door|storm door}}\n#: {{mero|en|doorlite|handle|hinge|jamb|knob|latch}}\n#: {{near-syn|en|gate|portal}}\n#: {{co|en|bathroom '''door''', bedroom '''door''', '''door'''key, exterior '''door''', interior '''door'''}}\n#* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=5|passage=Then everybody once more knelt, and soon the blessing was pronounced. The choir and the clergy trooped out slowly, {{...}}, down the nave to the western '''door'''. {{...}} At a seemingly immense distance the surpliced group stopped to say the last prayer.}}\n#* {{RQ:Allingham China Governess|chapter=20|passage=&lsquo;No. I only opened the '''door''' a foot and put my head in. The street lamps shine into that room. I could see him. He was all right. Sleeping like a great grampus. Poor, poor chap.’}}\n# {{lb|en|metonymically|chiefly in the plural}} A building with a door, especially a {{l|en|house}}.\n#: {{syn|en|home|house|place}}\n#: {{ux|en|His house is three '''doors''' down.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He went five '''doors''' up the road to the bank.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|month=June|author=Richard D. Kutz|title=Up the Park|publisher=First Books|isbn=9781592997923|page=71|text=We walked three '''doors''' up the street where we stopped in front 71 Richard D. Kutz.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2015-02-02|author=Laurel Deedrick-Mayne|title=A Wake For The Dreamland|publisher=FriesenPress|isbn=9781460258545|page=24|text=\"...The storage room is about, oh, three '''doors''' down, on the left. I'll point it out as we go by. Pay attention so you know where you have to come back to. Only then it'll be — let me see — about five '''doors''' down on your right.\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2024-03-26|author=Julia Dahl|title=Run You Down: A Novel|publisher=Macmillan + ORM|isbn=9781466841925|text=A woman pushes a stroller in the direction of the synagogue, and another, just one '''door''' down from Pessie's apartment, is unloading groceries from her minivan.}}\n# Any flap, etc., that opens like a door.\n#: {{ux|en|the 24 '''doors''' in an Advent calendar}}\n#: {{co|en|cupboard '''door'''}}\n# {{lb|en|immigration}} An entry point.\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} A means of approach or access.\n#: {{ux|en|Learning is the '''door''' to wisdom.}}\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} A [[possibility]].\n#: {{coi|en|to leave the '''door''' open}}\n#: {{coi|en|all '''doors''' are open to somebody}}\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} A [[barrier]].\n#: {{ux|en|Keep a '''door''' on your anger.}}\n# {{lb|en|computing|dated}} A {{l|en|software}} mechanism by which a user can interact with a {{l|en|program}} running remotely on a {{l|en|bulletin board system}}. See {{w|BBS door}}.\n# The proceeds from entrance fees and/or ticket sales at a venue such as a bar or nightclub, especially in relation to portion paid to the entertainers.\n#: {{uxi|en|The bar owner gives each band a percentage of the '''door''' and charges customers more to get in.}}\n\n{{col3|en|title=Parts of doors (six panel)\n|top rail\n|panel\n|1st mullion\n|cross rail\n|lock style\n|second mulion\n|lock rail\n|frame\n|lock set\n|third mullion\n|sticking\n|bottom rail\n|witness panel\n|witness line\n|lite\n|glazing\n|casing\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|mother-in-law door|when God closes a door he opens a window\n|a creaking door hangs longest\n|a creaking door hangs long on its hinges\n|a golden key can open any door\n|air door\n|ashdump door\n|at church every time the doors are open\n|at church every time the doors swing open\n|at Death's door\n|at death's door\n|at someone's door\n|at the door|kitty door\n|at the door of\n|attic door\n|automatic door\n|back door\n|back-door pilot\n|baize door\n|bang down the door\n|bang like a dunny door|five-piece door|one foot out the door|Shaker door\n|bang like a dunny door in a gale\n|bang like a shithouse door\n|bang on the door|build a better mousetrap and the world will beat a path to your door\n|bang the door down\n|barndoor\n|barn door\n|barn doors\n|beat Jack out of doors\n|beat my neighbour out of doors\n|beat your neighbour out of doors\n|behind closed doors\n|blower door\n|blow the doors off\n|boy-next-door\n|boy next door\n|butterfly door\n|car door\n|carriage door\n|cat door\n|cellar-door,cellar door\n|central door locking\n|check at the door\n|church-door\n|church door\n|clack door\n|closed door\n|close one's doors\n|close the door\n|close the door on\n|close the stable door after the horse has bolted\n|darken a church door\n|darken someone's door\n|dead door\n|death door\n|dock door\n|dog door\n|doggie door\n|don't let the door hit you on the way out\n|door alarm\n|door-bell\n|doorbell\n|door bitch\n|door brake\n|doorbuster\n|doorbusting\n|doorcase\n|door chain\n|doorcheek\n|door closer\n|Door County\n|door drawer\n|door entry system\n|doorflap\n|door-frame\n|door frame\n|doorframe\n|door game\n|doorgame\n|door god\n|door handle\n|doorhanger\n|door h